segments.text: My first question is, how did you get interested in athletics?
Oh, pretty much, well, my brother got me started in athletics.
When I was in the third grade, there was a man who came to my elementary school who was trying to start a track team, and he...
My brother stayed after school.
He was two years older than I was.
He stayed after school and worked out with the team and he picked the people he wanted on the team.
He said, I've got a sister who likes to run.
We always like, we had elementary school relays and relay races in school time and I always enjoyed running for some reason.
I just was made for it, I guess.
And he told the coach about me and she said, we'll have her stay after school tomorrow and we'll practice.
So that's really how I got started, was my brother pretty much told the coach that I wanted to run.
And so I stayed afterwards and made his team and ran into him in the summer track program.
Did you run with the boys or did you run against girls?
At that point, I think we pretty much just all ran together because we were pretty young.
He just kind of lined us up and we raced and he looked at us.
picked who he thought was the best.
This particular coach, Carl Robbins in Fort Worth, he had never run track in his life.
He was just a man who wanted to start a track team.
I don't know why, I never had to ask him why he was interested in that area, but he
He was the kind of coach that didn't push you to win just as long as you tried and you got a reward.
He would have relay track meets where if you just ran, everybody got a win and everybody got a reward.
And so I had a good experience young because I wasn't pushed.
And as a matter of fact, my parents didn't even come to see me run the whole first year that I ran track.
So I think it was kind of good because it wasn't a do or die like it is now.
Did you ever compete in any other sports besides track and field?
No.
In high school, we...
I'm not really that old, but we really didn't have anything.
That's why I was a junior.
I competed in AAU and the Junior Olympics, Keto Lab, in the summertime, summer programs.
But the only athletic programs that we had when I was in high school was tennis and swimming, and I put track in.
Later they put volleyball and basketball after I was all done with school.
So I really just picked track and stuck with that and didn't do anything else.
But I may have been different in that I had other things going on.
I have played half-court basketball, and I've played volleyball, but it was intramurals in high school.
Should women choose sports which they prefer, or should they choose sports, choose those sports which are more popular, such as gymnastics and figure skating?
I guess that would apply to now, I guess.
Um, they should, I think they should pick the sport that's best suited for them, and that they like, if they're going to want to go anywhere in that sport.
As a matter of fact, I get phone calls from parents all the time, wanting a chicken around his table.

who's daughter likes track but she's also good in basketball and she's good in volleyball and coaches are pushing her to do all three but she doesn't want to and obviously the girl has a lot of talent and I would say always go with the thing that you like best if you plan to try to
There's different levels of competition.
If you're trying to go to the top level to do what you should do, you've got to do something that you're going to like.
And whether it's popular or not, it doesn't really matter.
That's true.
About the other professional sports for women are tennis and golf.
Concerning the professional level, why do you feel women have made less money in individual sports, and why have women's professional teams struggled and oftentimes failed?
I don't really know why women don't get paid as much as men because I think people enjoy watching women play more than they like watching men play in different sports.
As far as track, they seem to be in the indoor meet when the women, they don't have very many women races.
They don't have a full scale in track meets.
A lot of times in the indoor meets they'll have a full scale men's events.
When you get to the women's events, they only have four or five events.
It's getting better, but when I was running it wasn't, it was not evenly distributed.
And I don't know why, because the people enjoy it when women run.
I don't know, I can't really answer that because I don't run.
I just don't understand.
You know, I'm not really a women's libero.
I guess it's gonna come some day.
Maybe it's just the fact that the women need to demand it.
I mean, they'd probably pay it if they demanded it, like the men do.
Why do women's professional teams struggle and often times fail at basketball and stuff like that?
At the professional level?
No, a lot of towns don't really, they don't book those teams to come in.
And that's probably part of the reason.
As a star female athlete, you probably experienced many things which non-athletic girls did not experience.
Did you ever feel you were treated differently from your peers in terms of dating, social activities, and interactions with non-athletic females?
Yeah, definitely.
It was real hard for me in high school.
Before I hit high school, it wasn't that big a deal because I ran for my father.
And the girls on the team were all friends.
You get to high school where you've got competition between girls and even girls from other schools.
If you're good, you're hated.
It's always that way.
If you're pretty, you're hated.
If you're popular, you're hated.
And that's the way it was for me.
I was popular within my school.

because I was a varsity cheerleader and on homecoming court and stuff like that so I got some things that let's me know that I was popular but I was disliked by a lot of girls because I did what I wanted to do
I think it will always be.
You think that was the sole reason you may be disliked because you were an athlete or because of the girls who disliked me.
They disliked me because I got a lot of publicity and started Fort Worth Star Telegram.
I think because I won a lot of things within the school and I think it was just jealousy.
But at the time I didn't understand that because
I mean, there were a lot of girls that I didn't like simply because they boasted.
And I didn't like that.
I never had.
But I was very, very shy.
I never said very much to anybody.
And kept to myself pretty much.
So that really wouldn't have been a reason for that.
I would say that was definitely one, and I think women.
I think a man will respect another man for his talents in that level, but in the youth.
When you get to college, it's a little bit different.
But women, for some reason, are jealous about women who see fame and fortune and do good things.
That's interesting.
What value did athletics teach you, and what do you feel people should gain from athletics?
It teaches you discipline.
Probably more than anything.
Because many times that I didn't want to go work out, you know, it was 6, 7 o'clock at night.
And at that time we didn't even have a team going to school.
And I didn't want to go.
I wanted to go to the basketball game.
I wanted to play football.
And I had to do it because it was something that I wanted.
I think that's the biggest plus in any sport or athletics is discipline, learn to discipline yourself.
You know, if you want something, you've got to work to get it.
It's not going to get you to it.
No matter how good you are, you still have to work or else you're going to lose it.
And I think that's a good thing.
As a female athlete at Texas A&M, did you feel female athletes were considered by their male counterparts as serious athletes?
For some reason I do at A&M now.
It may be different in other schools.
And I had a girl here from the Italian group who were discussing this.
And she asked me if I ever was called a jock.
And I said, no, not really.
Until I got out of college, I was never called a jock.
I was called a jock.
And at A&M, it seems like it's a unique school anyway, but it seems like they respect you for the talents.
And they don't cut you down.
They support you 110%.
It just goes that way for me.
That's good.
You were a very successful athlete at Texas A&M.
Despite all of your accomplishments, I found very little information on you in both the local newspaper and the battalion.
Do you feel you received your just recognition as an athlete, and do you think that you would have received more if you were a male?
Oh...
I don't know, to be real honest.
I probably got more publicity
than any other women at the time that I was playing in.
Probably more than any woman that had ever attended A&M as far as I played.
And they put a big picture in the paper when I made the team.
I was in there quite often and
I don't think I was, I felt like at the time I received a lot of justice, but if you compared me to a male of a similar quality, a male would have gotten more publicity than I did.
Curtis did to a skill level, and he was always on his way.
every newspaper, every afternoon.
Whereas I might get an article in there once every two weeks or something, or just right after the tragedy.
But Jerry Wagner and the eagle was very, very good to me when I was here.
And like I said,
I never was disappointed in the publicity that I got, but it wasn't on an equal level with women by no means.
And it never has been, not even when I was in high school.
And I got a lot of publicity when I was in high school, probably more than any other female athlete at that time.
Probably since, if I'm not wrong.
After I made the Olympic team,
which was the ultimate goal for me, and it's probably the ultimate goal for any amateur athlete.
I didn't get near the publicity and had on the fact that I thought I should have.

And as a matter of fact, my family, they were basically, and we went to Washington, and they honored all the athletes in Washington, and I talked to a lot of kids who were from small towns, and Fort Worth is not small.
And they were saying that they had like a day for them, like when you walk in the day.
They were giving the kids with the city, you know, they were giving luggage with their initials on it.
And really, this one guy was a wrestler that I was talking to that got all this stuff.
And there were some other athletes that were really highly recognized from high school and brought home and took a tape for it.
And that's great.
Small towns, but still.
Whereas I didn't really get anything.
I think A&M was pretty proud of me.
I got a little bit of publicity, but that was it.
Probably less publicity after I made the team than what I got after the track meet after I did well in the track meet, which I think is really sad.
When you were talking about Curtis Dickey, were you talking about him as a track athlete or as a football player?
Did you get a lot more as a track athlete?
No, well...
Well, once track season started, he did, and it was a never-ending thing for him because it was really good.
And he went from football to track, and he got a lot of publicity in the track season.
Okay, the Title IX section of the Equal Rights Amendment of 72 guarantees women equality with men in all areas of athletics.

Did you at any time feel the women's athletic program at Texas A&M was treated equally with the men's athletic program in terms of housing, scholarships, equipment, or benefits, or anything like that?
As far as housing, no.
I was on full scholarship, and they put me in Spence Hall, which is one of the four homes, and that was the women's athletic room.
And boys were over at King Hall, and my husband played football for A&M for
I would say definitely not.
I think it's better than it was at any other Southwest Conference school.
We have marvelous facilities, but when I was at A&M, we didn't have the locker room they do now.
I think A&M is trying to have the best women's program of any of the schools, and I think they probably do in the conference.
I think Texas is pretty good.
I really couldn't have any complaints because we flew to nationals every year and we had nice uniforms.
We traveled on the band, which I think I would probably complain that maybe we couldn't get big Graham buses like the men's team did.
If we're comparing the women's track team to the men's track team, I would say we're pretty much on an equal basis.
If you compare us to the football team, we're not, but then we don't make as much money as they do either.
A lot of women will complain that no one gets exactly what all the men's teams get, but even the men's team don't get equal proportions, so how can you expect that when you're on the women's team?
I'm pretty level-headed in that.
I've always had proper shoes and uniforms and expense money and all that.
So I really don't have any complaints in that area.
I think definitely there's a little bit of a difference there, but it's not...
As a result of the Title IX, there was a tremendous increase in the budget of women's athletics at A&M.
During your years here, the budget increased from $104,000 to $420,000.
Was the increase in the budget evident to you during your years here?
We...
The first year I was running for A&M, which was my sophomore year, and I was the only one on a full scholarship.
And there were a few partials.
And even the coach didn't make very much money.
And then the next year, my junior year, it was like we had...
five full scholarship women athletes.
As a matter of fact, we had more women on scholarship on the women's team than what the men had on their team.
And, of course, then it was separate coaches.
So I thought that was really interesting that we had more money than they did.
And it was real hard for the men to accept some of the men that were on their team that would walk on or that were only getting books and tuition.
And they'd compare themselves to this other girl over here who was the one that had scholarship or full scholarship and said, I can't do it.
So you could definitely tell, and the coach got a bigger increase also.
So you could definitely tell that we had more money when they came in.
From its inception, most colleges and the NCAA had been against Title IX.
They argued that an equal funding of men's and women's athletics would be an economic disaster for college athletics.
Do you feel this is a viable reason to disallow women an equal opportunity with men to enjoy athletics?
Well, I know that some of the schools have really bucked it.
You know, they don't want, they don't want the men in these programs equal.
I don't think that's the case at A&M.
I know some of the schools are that way and they've even totally cut out some of their women's programs.
I think that they need to accept it and that's the way it's going to be and do the best they can.
I can't believe that they're having that problem now.
It's been, when I graduated in 79, and it was kind of tough when I was like a junior, senior, but it's been long enough now that I can't imagine them accepting it.
University of Houston, for example, they have one coach.
Well, we do too at A&M now, and the men and women's teams are under one coach coming.
I don't think that he is going to say, well, I'm going to let the women's program say what they want to.
Women groups have fought for the separation of women's athletics from men's.
They feel the only way for women's athletics to prosper is for women to run their own programs.
In 1982, the NCAA ended the AIAW as an institution.
To be the best future for women athletics lies with the NCAA or should they run their own programs?
Well, as long as the people who are in the head office are going to be fair and equal, I think it's best to move on.
Because it's silly.
One rule, for example, is I transferred as a freshman from the University of Nevada to A&M, and I could compete and not get scholarships.
If they went ahead and waived it and let me transfer for various reasons, I had to go before the Ethics and Eligibility Committee.
But for a woman, you could transfer then under AIW.
You could run, but you couldn't be on scholarship.
The men, it was the opposite.
If you transferred in, you were an ineligible athlete, you could be on scholarship, but you couldn't compete.
So it's real stupid.
I think it needs to be under one, but I think they need to be fair and equal if they're going to do that.
I'm glad it went NCAA.
I like their rules.
They've been around for a long time.
They're doing something right.
AIAW was good.
It was okay.
And at that time, all the teams were members of it.
I don't think it can split.
There for a year, they had AIAW and NCAA.
And schools got their choice.
You could go AIAW or NCAA.
So you had a split there.
And that was silly.
You need one governing body.
They all need to be in one.
And I think men and women should be in the same.
Because if you don't, you're never going to be that equal part.
It's not ever going to be there.
Because you've got to be two different...
So I thought that was a good move.
A lot of people didn't like that.
I mean, women's athletic director was Kay Dawn.
Kay Dawn was very against it.
Yeah, but she was, but I think it was better in the end for us.
Why do you feel our society is not so more interested in the path towards women's sports?
And what do you feel the level of future interest will be?
What do you feel our society has not shown more interest in the past towards women's sports, and what do you feel the level of future interest will be like in women's basketball?
Well, I think the reason why they haven't in the past is because they haven't had that many things for women.
You know, it's just now that, like for example, what I was saying, in 75, I graduated from high school,
Well, until I was a junior, they didn't have any UIL.
This is in Fort Worth, the Metroplex area.
Fort Worth and Dallas schools, Arlington, they didn't even have UIL sports for girls.

And they finally put that in because I know in Fort Worth, my dad complained about it enough, and they finally said, we'll try it as a pilot program, which meant four schools out of like 10 in Fort Worth, they let them try it, and if it worked, then they would put it in all schools in my senior year.
And so I think that's one drawback is the fact that they haven't had all those things available.
And even at A&M now, you know, soccer needs to be NCAA.
It's a club right now.
I know some other ruling, I'm not sure what it is.
And it needs to, it should be, we should have a gymnastics program.
We don't.
I know you can't have everything because you probably don't have the funding for it, but that's part of the drawback where men's,
Since when my brother went to high school, they had track, wrestling, football, basketball, baseball, and they don't have any of those.
They still don't have softball in a lot of schools.
And that's an NCAA program in college.
So I think that's a big problem.
But I think we're getting over that now.
They're adding a little bit at a time.
It's just like the marathon not being an event for such a long time.
400-meter hurdles or 300-meter hurdles in high school for girls.
They didn't have that as an event for a long time, yet you go to college the next year and they have it.
So we need to have the same things in the high schools that we have in colleges.
It just doesn't...
measure.
So they're getting over that right now.
It's definitely a plus.
Do you feel athletes should live apart from the remainder of the student body?
And do you feel the integration of athletes with the regular students would hurt or help them in their pursuit of education?
Personally, I think they should live apart because athletes
They're coming and going at different times.
Maybe, for instance, the cafeteria closing.
I remember the swimmers had to go to the snack bar across the way over at Mosher.
And that was always because the cafeteria was closed when they got through the workouts.
Uh-huh.
Uh, you're getting out at earlier hours.
We were constantly being yelled at from the Corps of Women, Head of Women, whatever they were called, in the Resident Advisors.
When we got into the workout, they were saying, it's time to be quiet.
It's bedtime.
Well, shoot, we were just getting into the workout.
And hadn't had any leisure time.
It might have been 5.30 or 6.
So, I think...
I think it's good if they can live apart because of those type things, but I don't think it hurts if they do live together.
Women athletes seem to fit in better with regular students.
I would say much more than men athletes.
the basketball players who walk a little taller than everybody else.
And that's not to knock them down, but it's not in every athlete, but in some it is.
It's just like, for example, when they threw the pizza guy down the stairs, they gave him a year and a half of the cookie.
You know, they think they can breath house everything.
The football players.
It was the football players.
They took the pizza and threw it down the stairs and came home.
You know, I think...
That if they were forced to live with the regular students, that it would be good in that instance.
But if I had to make a choice, I'd rather have them live separately.
Their food requirements are a little bit different also.
Speaking from an athlete's perspective, what is the role of the college athlete and what is your opinion of having only volunteer college athletics in place of scholarship athletics?
I don't think volunteer will be good.
I think if somebody's got a talent that they should be rewarded for the extra hours that they put in.

You know, you're out there, you're traveling on weekends, it makes it harder to study for an exam, you're missing a major exam on a Friday, you're traveling all weekend in a van, you don't want to come clubbing in Texas in a van.
Because of those extra things, I definitely think that you should be rewarded for it.
The athletes that, I think that the walk-on thing, it should always be there.
I don't think you should have to be on scholarship to be on the team, because if they can walk on out there and be on the team, that's good too.
What is the role of the college athlete?
I think the role of a college athlete is to represent the school to the best of their ability.
Not necessarily wearing dresses to and from, which a lot of the coaches used to do that.
But know that when you go into a restaurant, you've got your sweats on, so let's take some in.
But those people know you're an athlete and that you're responsible to show them that you're
a good person, where they don't carry their breath spot down, no obscenities and that sort of thing, but to represent yourself well, both on and off the field.
Do you feel the 1980 Olympic boycott was the correct action to take by our government?
That this action was fully understood by both yourself and other teammates, and will the Olympic Games ever be the same?
It wasn't understood by the teammates at all, myself or any of the other teams.
They were very bitter about it.
I don't agree with it.
I think it was a mistake.
you know, what's happened now.
We got a little miffed because I didn't come to our Olympics.
I don't think the Olympics will ever, ever be the same because every year there's going to be one country that's going to boycott the one that's going to happen.
And years ago, that didn't happen.
I guess, really, since 68, things have really started changing in the Olympic realm.
You had terrorist attacks and stuff like that.
Because of terrorism, also, it won't be the same.
You're always in fear of that.
even if you're going as an athlete.
If I had gone to Moscow, I think I'd have been a little bit nervous.
But I think we're going to have to try to keep the politics out as much as possible.
And that's real hard.
One reason why I completely quit competing was because I was sick and tired of all politics after 1980.
I had originally planned to get back into it the next year and start competing again.
And I tried working out.
I just couldn't get on with it.
It just...
Because I really got involved, and I really understood just how nasty that event really was.
And until you reach that level, you don't really know what it's like.
But, you know, I think it was terrible.
At the time I made the team, I was real excited about making the team.
And, you know, we got our watches and our rings, and everybody from the hometown said,
that, but then it sunk in probably a little bit later in the year when I saw the Olympics on television and how stupid it was.
And then also they backtracked a few years later, and the grain embargoes lifted.
No big deal.
But you can't ever give the memories back.
So I think it was a big mistake, and I don't think the Olympics saved all the athletes
I don't think I met an athlete on the whole Olympic team, not just the track team, but on the rowing team, the wrestling team, that agreed with it.
I cannot remember one that said no.
I just don't remember.
Yeah, I do agree with it.
And a lot of them wouldn't even shake President Carter's hand when he went to the White House and he took him to the country.
They wouldn't even shake his hand.
It was really a bad, bad scene.
And for some of those, the ones that were really bitter at that time that I remember were the ones that had made a team before.
It was their second Olympic team or third.
Because for me, it was all new, and I was all excited.
They knew what they were missing, and they were real bad bitter.
It hit me a little bit later on.
Like that.
